The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, February 05, 2004 				 Oil payouts ease deficit pangs
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Feb. 4: The public sector oil companies have come to the rescue of the government on the fiscal front, declaring a total interim dividend of Rs 2,6739.5 crore for the current financial year. 																								ONGC leads the pack with a Rs 1,678 crore dividend at 140 per cent followed by Indian Oil Corporation, which has paid an interim dividend of Rs 479 crore at 50 per cent of its equity.																								Gail (India) is ranked third with a dividend of Rs 227.83 crore while Oil India comes next with a dividend of Rs 126 crore. Bharat Petroleum and Hindustan Petroleum Corporation have paid interim dividends of Rs 119.2 crore and Rs 103.8 crore respectively. 																								Petroleum minister Ram Naik told the parliamentary consultative committee attached to his ministry last night that all downstream companies had already presented their cheques while those of ONGC and OIL were expected to come in soon.																								The minister also disclosed that the contracts for 20 more oil exploration blocks and another eight blocks for coal-bed methane exploration would be signed on Friday. 
